About a year has passed since my first "awakening."
[r]I don't even have the slightest idea that my experiences in that world were dreams. [r]
The quantity and quality of memories, as well as the sense of reality, are so different from normal dreams.[l][r]
That, that layered city, is definitely a world I have experienced firsthand.[r]
I was born there, grew up there, lived there, crashed there, wandered there, and died there.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

[cm  ]
[tb_start_text mode=3 ]
But at the same time, he also has memories of his life in modern Japan and his past.[l][r]
Born in a rural area, he had an ordinary childhood, then went on to a science and engineering school, studied aerodynamics and mechanical engineering, got his degree, and joined his current company. [r]
I feel that these memories are real, and my parents and grandparents are still alive and well in my hometown.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

[cm  ]
[tb_start_text mode=3 ]
So, let me ask myself a question.
Which memory is more real? [l][r]
[r]The answer is, "They're both real." It may seem contradictory, but... [l][r]
[r]After asking myself these questions over and over again, I eventually came to the conclusion that it didn't really matter. [r]
There are always questions that can't be answered, like the "5 minutes ago" hypothesis.[l][r]
However, even after coming to terms with it like that, I was left with a feeling of doubt or sentimentality that I just couldn't shake off.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

[cm  ]
[tb_start_text mode=3 ]
I wonder what is happening to that city and those girls now.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

